{
  "question_type": "choice",
  "question": "You are tasked with performing a large number of search queries on a static dataset of size N. You are strictly forbidden from using O(N) additional space (beyond the input array), and you must provide the best possible worst-case time complexity per query. Which approach is most appropriate under these constraints?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Linear search on the unsorted array to avoid any preprocessing overhead or extra space.",
    "B": "In-place sort followed by binary search to achieve O(log N) worst-case query time.",
    "C": "A hash table with chaining to achieve O(1) average-case search time for all queries.",
    "D": "A hash table with open addressing to ensure O(1) worst-case search time without extra space."
  },
  "correct_answer": "B",
  "explanation": "The constraints specify 'no O(N) extra space' and 'worst-case guarantees' for 'many queries' on 'static data'. \n1. Linear search (A) has a worst-case of O(N), which is inefficient for many queries.\n2. Hashing (C and D) typically requires O(N) extra space to store the table and handles collisions. Even with open addressing, the worst-case time complexity for a standard hash table is O(N), not O(1).\n3. Sorting the data in-place (e.g., using Heapsort) requires O(1) extra space. Once sorted, binary search provides a guaranteed O(log N) worst-case time complexity per query. This is the optimal worst-case performance given the space constraint.",
